FAQs about hotels in Detroit

On average, 3-star hotels in Detroit cost $288 per night, and 4-star hotels in Detroit are $255 per night. If you're looking for something really special, a 5-star hotel in Detroit can be found for $301 per night, on average (based on Booking.com prices).
The average price per night for a 3-star hotel in Detroit this weekend is $297 or, for a 4-star hotel, $323. Looking for something even fancier? 5-star hotels in Detroit for this weekend cost around $607 per night, on average (based on Booking.com prices).
On average, it costs $258 per night to book a 3-star hotel in Detroit for tonight. You'll pay around $258 if you choose to stay in a 4-star hotel tonight, while a 5-star hotel in Detroit will cost around $283, on average (based on Booking.com prices).
Many families visiting Detroit loved staying at The Detroit Club , Shinola Hotel , and Hotel David Whitney, Autograph Collection .
Some of the best hotels in Detroit near MotorCity Casino include Stylish Cozy Studio in Detroit , Shinola Hotel and ROOST Detroit .
Travelers who stayed in Detroit near Detroit Metro Airport (DTW) have said good things about The Westin Detroit Metropolitan Airport , Embassy Suites by Hilton Detroit Metro Airport , and Hilton Garden Inn Detroit Metro Airport .
Shinola Hotel , AC Hotel Detroit at the Bonstelle , and Atheneum Suite Hotel are some of the popular hotels in Detroit.
For hotels in Detroit that serve highly-rated breakfasts, try DoubleTree Suites by Hilton Hotel Detroit Downtown - Fort Shelby , Detroit Foundation Hotel , and The Siren Hotel, an Ash Hotel .
These hotels in Detroit are highly rated by couples: AC Hotel Detroit at the Bonstelle , Element Detroit at the Metropolitan , and Hotel David Whitney, Autograph Collection .

What Guests Said About Detroit:

  • Review score
    8.0

    It was cold!! We went in January so that is expected.

    It was cold!! We went in January so that is expected. The ride from the airport was about 30 minutes by ride share. There was a car show a few 100 feet from the hotel we stayed at, and although it was kind of basic for being in the Motor City, it was still a good car show. I do love that Detroit is in a Renaissance because it is a beautiful city with magnificent architecture. The people we met from Detroit were mostly friendly and welcoming. We attended a Lions game and were there supporting the opposing team. There were no issues and it even made for a great conversation starter. I'd go back!!
    Guest review by
    Lisa
    United States
  • Review score
    10.0

    If you love New York City but are a little tired of the...

    If you love New York City but are a little tired of the swarming tourists and insane traffic, visit Detroit. Downtown is wonderful, with great shops and restaurants, a vibrant street scene with pedestrians and musicians, world class museums, and amazing architecture. Don't miss the lobby of the Book Tower or Michigan Central Station.
    Guest review by
    John
    United States
  • Review score
    10.0

    Hadn't previously visited Detroit.

    Hadn't previously visited Detroit. Attended a great concert at the Fillmore, ate at Mom's Spaghetti, toured the Motown Museum, and more. If you like corned beef, you must visit Lon's! Highly recommended. I'll return for another visit.
    Guest review by
    Mark
    United States
  • Review score

    Detroit is my home but I have lived on the west coast for...

    Detroit is my home but I have lived on the west coast for many years. It was wonderful to see how the city has bounced back and there is so much to do there. Corktown, Greek town, waterfront restaurants and different venues featuring celebrations for Thanksgiving was great.
    Guest review by

    Took my sister visiting with me and my husband on a tour...

    Took my sister visiting with me and my husband on a tour starting at the Riverwalk. She was stunned as to how beautiful Detroit is. The neighborhoods we drove through enabled her to discount all the negative information she read about and seen by the media. Many pictures were taken to share with other residents in California.

    The Henry Ford Museum and Greenfield Village were...

    The Henry Ford Museum and Greenfield Village were outstanding. The Detroit Institute of Art was a big surprise. It is huge with amazing pieces. The Industrial Murals by Diego Rivera were a favorite of mine. The Motown Museum was fully booked , but people say it’s wonderful. The restored Union Station didn’t open until 5:00, so we couldn’t see it.

How does it work?

    It starts with a booking

    The only way to leave a review is to first make a booking. That's how we know our reviews come from real guests who have stayed at the property.

  • 2

    Followed by a trip

    Followed by a trip

    When guests stay at the property, they check out how quiet the room is, how friendly the staff is, and more.

  • 3

    And finally, a review

    And finally, a review

    After their trip, guests tell us about their stay. We check for naughty words and verify the authenticity of all guest reviews before adding them to our site.
